{"questionId":"9070459","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A mixture of 1.00 mol SO<sub>2</sub>(g), 2.00 mol O<sub>2</sub>(g) and 1.00 mol SO<sub>3</sub>(g) is placed in a 1.00 dm<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;container and allowed to reach equilibrium.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">2SO<sub>2</sub>(g) + O<sub>2</sub>(g) <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" \\rightleftharpoons \">\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">⇌</mo>\n</math></span>&nbsp;2SO<sub>3</sub>(g)</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>The rate constant for a reaction doubles when the temperature is increased from&nbsp;25.0 °C to 35 °C.</p>\n<p>Calculate the activation energy, <em>E</em><sub>a</sub>, in kJ mol<sup>−1</sup> for the reaction using section 1 and 2 of&nbsp;the data booklet.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>«</strong><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\ln \\frac{{{k_1}}}{{{k_2}}} = \\frac{{{E_a}}}{R}\\left( {\\frac{1}{{{T_2}}} - \\frac{1}{{{T_1}}}} \\right)\">\n  <mi>ln</mi>\n  <mo>⁡</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <msub>\n          <mi>k</mi>\n          <mn>1</mn>\n        </msub>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <msub>\n          <mi>k</mi>\n          <mn>2</mn>\n        </msub>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <msub>\n          <mi>E</mi>\n          <mi>a</mi>\n        </msub>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mi>R</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mfrac>\n        <mn>1</mn>\n        <mrow>\n          <mrow>\n            <msub>\n              <mi>T</mi>\n              <mn>2</mn>\n            </msub>\n          </mrow>\n        </mrow>\n      </mfrac>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mfrac>\n        <mn>1</mn>\n        <mrow>\n          <mrow>\n            <msub>\n              <mi>T</mi>\n              <mn>1</mn>\n            </msub>\n          </mrow>\n        </mrow>\n      </mfrac>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span><strong>»</strong></p>\n<p>T<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>«</strong>273 +&nbsp;35 =<strong>» </strong>308 K <strong><em>AND </em></strong>T<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>«</strong>273 +&nbsp;25 =<strong>» </strong>298 K</p>\n<p><em>E</em><sub>a</sub>&nbsp;= 52.9 <strong>«</strong>kJ mol<sup>–1</sup><strong>»</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em>Award </em><strong><em>[2] </em></strong><em>for correct final answer.</em></p>\n<p><strong><em>[2 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9070459","referenceCode":"18M.2.hl.TZ2.d","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"The rate constant for a reaction doubles when the temperature is increased from 25.0 °C to 35 °C. Calculate the activation energy, Ea, in kJ mol−1 for the reaction using section 1 ","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 16: Chemical kinetics","16.2 Activation energy","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 16: Chemical kinetics"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}